Session Summary (2026-04-20)

Picked up from v7 where color hinting was built but untested. First run revealed two bugs before any real testing could happen:

Bug 1 — Wrong positional argument. cut_clips.py expects a clips CSV as its first argument, not the video file. The video file goes via -s. Clips CSV lives at footage/magic_clips/magic_clips.csv.

Bug 2 — Color hint sampling wrong region. MediaPipe returns face-only bounding boxes. The score_color() function in color_utils.py samples the 40–75% height region of the box assuming full-body — on a face box that samples the chin/neck, not the shirt. Fixed by building extended boxes (face bottom + 2× face height downward) used only for color scoring; original face boxes still drive crop centering.

Color hint still not working reliably. Even after the fix, the crop wasn't targeting P1 (yellow shirt, right side). Root cause not yet confirmed — likely the lighting in this footage (desert shoot) is making HSV color scoring unreliable. Orange shirt test also failed. This is unresolved.

New debug tooling added:

write_debug_horizontal() — full-frame 1920x1080 debug video with detection boxes, green/gray labels, P-numbers. Renders as ...-horizontal_DEBUG.mp4 when -d is passed. Much easier to read than vertical debug.
Segment overlay on both debug outputs — top-left corner shows active segment number, time range, current timestamp, and active hint. Driven by the planning CSV.
Where to pick up next: The horizontal debug video should make it much easier to confirm which person the detector is actually selecting and why. Next step is either (a) implement positional hints (right/left) as a reliable fallback to color, or (b) watch the new horizontal debug and diagnose why color scoring is still picking the wrong person.